    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p><strong>Tomcat</strong> is just a servlet container, i.e. it implements only the servlets and JSP specification. <strong>Glassfish</strong> and <strong>JBoss</strong> are full Java EE servers (including stuff like EJB, JMS, ...), with Glassfish being the reference implementation of the latest Java EE 6 stack, but JBoss in 2010 was not fully supporting it yet.</p>\n<p>Tomcat, Glassfish, JBoss:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apache_Tomcat\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apache_Tomcat</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GlassFish\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GlassFish</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JBoss\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JBoss</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>They are also listed in this table:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_application_servers#Java\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_application_servers#Java</a></li>\n</ul>\n"
  }, {
